title: 410 Gap Road Native Plants Riddells Creek

items.title: Amphibromus spp.
items.content_text: ID to genus by Neville Walsh. A few plants growing in and beside our patch of creek (Sandy Creek). Pic shows the distinctive membranous ligule of the Amphibromus genus.

items.title: Daucus glochidiatus
items.content_text: New species record for this collection.

items.title: Hovea heterophylla
items.content_text: One white-flowered plant among many mauve-flowered plants.

items.title: Cassinia longifolia
items.content_text: Lovely pink-bud form of Cassinia longifolia. One seen in Sandy Ck Reserve last week too. I think they end up white-flowered.

items.title: Solanum laciniatum, Strepera graculina
items.content_text: Ate 8-10 fruit. Initially seen perched in tree and thought it was a Grey Currawong (see pic 2). Pic 3 shows tail feather markings confirming it is the Pied Currawong. Probably moulting.

items.title: Eucalyptus viminalis subsp. viminalis
items.content_text: Very old/large Manna Gum opposite 410 Gap Road, Riddells Creek. Large hollow is currently home to nesting Kookaburras. Full of life with Koalas, 2 x possum species and many other birds, animals and insects seen in and around it.

items.title: Poa labillardierei, Poa labillardierei var. labillardierei
